of Dirac equations
and their properties.

00:48:31.330 --> 00:48:35.410 align:middle line:90%
So do you have other questions?

00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:36.070 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:48:36.070 --> 00:48:38.153 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So we've seen
hints that this corresponds

00:48:38.153 --> 00:48:41.440 align:middle line:84%
to spin 1/2, but wouldn't
it make more sense

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:43.990 align:middle line:84%
to just define the
angular momentum operator

00:48:43.990 --> 00:48:46.550 align:middle line:84%
and see whether it has
eigenvalues or not?

00:48:46.550 --> 00:48:49.780 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that you would
need to quantize the theory,

00:48:49.780 --> 00:48:52.840 align:middle line:84%
but we haven't
quantized the theory.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:55.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, that would
be our next step.

00:48:55.190 --> 00:48:58.940 align:middle line:84%
So once we have found the full
set of classical solutions

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:00.590 align:middle line:90%
and now we can quantize it.

00:49:00.590 --> 00:49:04.538 align:middle line:84%
And once quantize it, then
we can actually really find

00:49:04.538 --> 00:49:05.455 align:middle line:90%
this angular momentum.

00:49:05.455 --> 00:49:08.080 align:middle line:90%


00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:09.190 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:10.930 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, actually,
I think that would

00:49:10.930 --> 00:49:16.450 align:middle line:84%
be one of your pset
problems to show yourself

00:49:16.450 --> 00:49:17.590 align:middle line:90%
that this is spin-half.

00:49:17.590 --> 00:49:20.410 align:middle line:90%


00:49:20.410 --> 00:49:23.080 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, but yeah.

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:23.950 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:49:23.950 --> 00:49:27.190 align:middle line:90%


00:49:27.190 --> 00:49:27.900 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:31.160 align:middle line:90%


00:49:31.160 --> 00:49:33.800 align:middle line:84%
So now we conclude
the discussion.

00:49:33.800 --> 00:49:35.225 align:middle line:90%
Now we can quantize the theory.

00:49:35.225 --> 00:49:44.680 align:middle line:90%


00:49:44.680 --> 00:49:46.885 align:middle line:84%
Now we can go to
the quantum system.

00:49:46.885 --> 00:49:58.730 align:middle line:90%


00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:06.270 align:middle line:84%
So the-- remember, the
action for the Dirac

00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:18.710 align:middle line:84%
is d4x psi bar gamma mu partial
mu psi partial mu minus m psi.

00:50:18.710 --> 00:50:25.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is the action which
gives us the Dirac equation.

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:28.810 align:middle line:90%


00:50:28.810 --> 00:50:31.570 align:middle line:84%
So in order to quantize
this, we first--

00:50:31.570 --> 00:50:36.450 align:middle line:84%
remember our procedure
to quantize a theory.

00:50:36.450 --> 00:50:41.540 align:middle line:84%
So we need to first find
the canonical momentum,

00:50:41.540 --> 00:50:45.710 align:middle line:84%
and we also need to impose the
canonical commutation relation,

00:50:45.710 --> 00:50:50.000 align:middle line:84%
and then we expand
the operators in terms

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:53.807 align:middle line:84%
of complete sets of
classical solutions,

00:50:53.807 --> 00:50:56.390 align:middle line:84%
and then that's corresponding
to the solutions to the operator

00:50:56.390 --> 00:50:58.490 align:middle line:90%
equations.

00:50:58.490 --> 00:51:02.630 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to find out what's
the canonical momentum for psi.

00:51:02.630 --> 00:51:05.780 align:middle line:90%


00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:08.490 align:middle line:84%
So as in the
complex scalar case,

00:51:08.490 --> 00:51:11.570 align:middle line:84%
we can treat the
psi and psi dagger

00:51:11.570 --> 00:51:15.410 align:middle line:84%
as independent variables
because of the--

00:51:15.410 --> 00:51:16.610 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:51:16.610 --> 00:51:19.970 align:middle line:84%
So then the canonical
momentum for psi--

00:51:19.970 --> 00:51:22.500 align:middle line:90%
if you look at this expression.

00:51:22.500 --> 00:51:26.720 align:middle line:84%
So you look at
the partial 0 psi.

00:51:26.720 --> 00:51:31.370 align:middle line:84%
Then you find-- so the
Lagrangian density--

00:51:31.370 --> 00:51:34.290 align:middle line:84%
if you look at that,
if I write it bit--

00:51:34.290 --> 00:51:37.760 align:middle line:90%
I have the form psi dagger.

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:47.790 align:middle line:84%
So this psi dagger gamma 0, and
then gamma 0 psi 0 psi, then

00:51:47.790 --> 00:51:49.290 align:middle line:90%
plus the rest of the terms.

00:51:49.290 --> 00:51:51.360 align:middle line:84%
So in order to find
the canonical momentum,

00:51:51.360 --> 00:51:56.200 align:middle line:84%
we are only interested in the
part of the Lagrangian density

00:51:56.200 --> 00:51:58.800 align:middle line:84%
which are related to the
derivative of psi-- or the time

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:00.000 align:middle line:90%
derivative.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:02.550 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
only term involving

00:52:02.550 --> 00:52:06.750 align:middle line:84%
time derivative of either
psi or psi bar or psi dagger.

00:52:06.750 --> 00:52:09.330 align:middle line:90%


00:52:09.330 --> 00:52:12.750 align:middle line:84%
So this gamma 0 squared
equal to minus 1--

00:52:12.750 --> 00:52:19.400 align:middle line:84%
so this is just i psi
dagger partial 0 psi.

00:52:19.400 --> 00:52:23.300 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can
immediately find out

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:31.650 align:middle line:84%
that the conjugate momentum for
psi is given by i psi dagger,

00:52:31.650 --> 00:52:34.695 align:middle line:84%
because you take a
derivative on psi 0--

00:52:34.695 --> 00:52:37.290 align:middle line:84%
partial 0 psi, you
just get i psi dagger.

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:43.680 align:middle line:84%
But the conjugate
momentum for psi dagger

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:44.775 align:middle line:90%
is actually equal to what?

00:52:44.775 --> 00:52:47.710 align:middle line:90%


00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:51.406 align:middle line:90%
So what is this?

00:52:51.406 --> 00:52:52.804 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: 0.

00:52:52.804 --> 00:52:55.850 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Thi is equal to
0 because there is no time

00:52:55.850 --> 00:53:00.190 align:middle line:90%
derivative on psi dagger.

00:53:00.190 --> 00:53:01.650 align:middle line:90%
So this tells you--

00:53:01.650 --> 00:53:05.440 align:middle line:90%


00:53:05.440 --> 00:53:09.350 align:middle line:84%
so this-- so the
fact that this--

00:53:09.350 --> 00:53:15.080 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0 tells you
actually the Dirac system--

00:53:15.080 --> 00:53:17.900 align:middle line:84%
the action-- this Dirac
system is actually

00:53:17.900 --> 00:53:18.845 align:middle line:90%
a constrained system.

00:53:18.845 --> 00:53:23.310 align:middle line:90%


00:53:23.310 --> 00:53:26.780 align:middle line:84%
So this is considered to be
a constraint, because you

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:29.320 align:middle line:90%
can no longer normally--

00:53:29.320 --> 00:53:36.790 align:middle line:84%
so remember, when we
say from the Lagrangian,

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:39.670 align:middle line:84%
you find the canonical
momentum, and then

00:53:39.670 --> 00:53:42.160 align:middle line:84%
you invert the
canonical momentum

00:53:42.160 --> 00:53:43.480 align:middle line:90%
to find the Hamiltonian.

00:53:43.480 --> 00:53:46.310 align:middle line:90%


00:53:46.310 --> 00:53:50.300 align:middle line:84%
But when you have this equal
to 0, you cannot invert it.

00:53:50.300 --> 00:53:54.530 align:middle line:84%
You cannot express your, say,
psi or psi dagger in terms

00:53:54.530 --> 00:53:56.330 align:middle line:90%
of pi or pi dagger.

00:53:56.330 --> 00:53:58.980 align:middle line:90%
And so this is a constrained.

00:53:58.980 --> 00:54:03.695 align:middle line:84%
So that means you actually
have a constrained system.

00:54:03.695 --> 00:54:07.510 align:middle line:84%
It means you have a
constrained system.

00:54:07.510 --> 00:54:11.380 align:middle line:84%
And frankly, constrained
systems are very annoying.

00:54:11.380 --> 00:54:15.830 align:middle line:90%


00:54:15.830 --> 00:54:19.740 align:middle line:90%
So they have involved lots of--

00:54:19.740 --> 00:54:21.420 align:middle line:84%
you have a lot of
formalism in order

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:23.400 align:middle line:84%
to, say, treat
constrained system--

00:54:23.400 --> 00:54:25.860 align:middle line:90%
to quantize them, et cetera.

00:54:25.860 --> 00:54:27.900 align:middle line:84%
But fortunately, in
this case, there's

00:54:27.900 --> 00:54:31.710 align:middle line:84%
actually a simple
trick to go around it.

00:54:31.710 --> 00:54:37.200 align:middle line:84%
And so now, I will not use
this full-fledged constrained

00:54:37.200 --> 00:54:38.460 align:middle line:90%
quantization to do the job.

00:54:38.460 --> 00:54:40.470 align:middle line:84%
I will just use a
simple trick which

00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:42.150 align:middle line:90%
will reach the same answer.

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:42.812 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

00:54:42.812 --> 00:54:44.520 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Is it like
the canonical momenta

00:54:44.520 --> 00:54:46.614 align:middle line:84%
not well-defined,
because I could integrate

00:54:46.614 --> 00:54:50.091 align:middle line:84%
by parts to move around
the time derivative

00:54:50.091 --> 00:54:52.760 align:middle line:84%
because I can move the
time derivative from psi

00:54:52.760 --> 00:54:54.080 align:middle line:90%
to psi dagger, right?

00:54:54.080 --> 00:54:55.740 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so
there's ambiguity.

00:54:55.740 --> 00:54:58.040 align:middle line:84%
So that's part of the
reflection that this

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:00.360 align:middle line:90%
is a constrained system.

00:55:00.360 --> 00:55:05.120 align:middle line:84%
So this is actually typical to
have these kind of constraints.

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:07.920 align:middle line:84%
It's typical whenever you
have a first-order system.

00:55:07.920 --> 00:55:11.000 align:middle line:84%
So here, it's different from
the Klein-Gordon action is

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:15.860 align:middle line:84%
because here, we only involving
the first derivative--

00:55:15.860 --> 00:55:18.350 align:middle line:84%
one derivative rather
than two derivatives.

00:55:18.350 --> 00:55:22.950 align:middle line:84%
And so this is not
our standard system.

00:55:22.950 --> 00:55:29.620 align:middle line:84%
So the way to go around
this is the following.

00:55:29.620 --> 00:55:33.230 align:middle line:84%
The way to go around
it is the following.

00:55:33.230 --> 00:55:38.500 align:middle line:84%
It's now-- so this equation--
if we look at this equation--

00:55:38.500 --> 00:55:42.490 align:middle line:90%


00:55:42.490 --> 00:55:44.850 align:middle line:84%
so this equation tells you
that the canonical momentum

00:55:44.850 --> 00:55:50.220 align:middle line:84%
conjugate to psi is
actually psi dagger.

00:55:50.220 --> 00:55:53.670 align:middle line:84%
So also here it's
a little bit funny,

00:55:53.670 --> 00:55:57.240 align:middle line:84%
because you remember
in the standard story,

00:55:57.240 --> 00:56:01.630 align:middle line:84%
the canonical momentum is
related to the time derivative.

00:56:01.630 --> 00:56:03.130 align:middle line:84%
And here, there's
no time derivative

00:56:03.130 --> 00:56:05.650 align:middle line:90%
here-- just psi dagger itself.

00:56:05.650 --> 00:56:08.350 align:middle line:84%
And this is another
indication that this

00:56:08.350 --> 00:56:11.440 align:middle line:90%
is a constraint rather than--

00:56:11.440 --> 00:56:12.130 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:56:12.130 --> 00:56:20.030 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, here, it tells you
that the dagger is, in fact,

00:56:20.030 --> 00:56:22.790 align:middle line:90%
the canonical moment of psi.

00:56:22.790 --> 00:56:24.670 align:middle line:90%
And now, we can just--

00:56:24.670 --> 00:56:26.530 align:middle line:84%
now in this
equation, we can just

00:56:26.530 --> 00:56:30.310 align:middle line:84%
try to interpret the psi
dagger as the momentum

00:56:30.310 --> 00:56:33.040 align:middle line:84%
rather than as the
configuration variable.

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:35.620 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's rewrite
the Lagrangian.

00:56:35.620 --> 00:56:38.620 align:middle line:84%
So the Lagrangian has
the following form--

00:56:38.620 --> 00:56:45.910 align:middle line:84%
minus i psi bar gamma mu
partial mu minus m psi.

00:56:45.910 --> 00:56:48.170 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
Lagrangian density.

00:56:48.170 --> 00:56:51.260 align:middle line:84%
So we'll rewrite it
as the following.

00:56:51.260 --> 00:56:54.800 align:middle line:84%
So let's first separate
the time derivative.

00:56:54.800 --> 00:56:56.440 align:middle line:90%
So this is psi dagger.

00:56:56.440 --> 00:57:01.420 align:middle line:84%
So just this term involving
the time derivative.

00:57:01.420 --> 00:57:06.570 align:middle line:84%
And then the rest, I have
psi bar gamma i partial

00:57:06.570 --> 00:57:08.160 align:middle line:90%
i minus m psi.

00:57:08.160 --> 00:57:12.570 align:middle line:84%
But here, they are no longer
involving the time derivative.

00:57:12.570 --> 00:57:17.540 align:middle line:84%
And now, we just interpret
this as the canonical momentum

00:57:17.540 --> 00:57:18.180 align:middle line:90%
for psi.

00:57:18.180 --> 00:57:24.660 align:middle line:90%


00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:27.240 align:middle line:84%
And then this is just
something involving

00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:30.450 align:middle line:90%
spatial derivative of psi.

00:57:30.450 --> 00:57:32.940 align:middle line:84%
And I just interpret this
as the Hamiltonian for psi.

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:45.440 align:middle line:90%


00:57:45.440 --> 00:57:47.120 align:middle line:84%
So this expression
just involving

00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:49.190 align:middle line:90%
psi dagger and the psi--

00:57:49.190 --> 00:57:50.990 align:middle line:84%
involving some
spatial derivative.

00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:55.160 align:middle line:84%
And so this is essentially
just some functions of psi--

00:57:55.160 --> 00:57:59.720 align:middle line:84%
pi psi and psi and maybe with
some spatial derivatives.

00:57:59.720 --> 00:58:04.330 align:middle line:84%
So now, you see that
this Lagrangian density--

00:58:04.330 --> 00:58:07.210 align:middle line:84%
actually, if I
interpret the diagram

00:58:07.210 --> 00:58:08.770 align:middle line:84%
as the canonical
momentum, then it

00:58:08.770 --> 00:58:11.170 align:middle line:84%
has the form of this
canonical transformation

00:58:11.170 --> 00:58:14.080 align:middle line:84%
to go from the Lagrangian
density to Hamiltonian.

00:58:14.080 --> 00:58:16.510 align:middle line:84%
And then I can just interpret
this as the Hamiltonian.

00:58:16.510 --> 00:58:21.180 align:middle line:90%


00:58:21.180 --> 00:58:24.856 align:middle line:84%
So now, I can just interpret
this as my Hamiltonian.

00:58:24.856 --> 00:58:28.800 align:middle line:90%


00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:32.635 align:middle line:90%
So we just treat--

00:58:32.635 --> 00:59:03.010 align:middle line:90%


00:59:03.010 --> 00:59:08.900 align:middle line:90%
so now, we just--

00:59:08.900 --> 00:59:14.540 align:middle line:84%
so this is-- so
psi dagger and psi.

00:59:14.540 --> 00:59:18.230 align:middle line:84%
And now, this is the
full phase space.

00:59:18.230 --> 00:59:21.210 align:middle line:84%
So this is the momentum
and this is the coordinate,

00:59:21.210 --> 00:59:26.318 align:middle line:84%
so this is the full space,
rather than previously, we

00:59:26.318 --> 00:59:28.235 align:middle line:84%
would interpret them as
a configuration space.

00:59:28.235 --> 00:59:31.970 align:middle line:90%


00:59:31.970 --> 00:59:37.690 align:middle line:84%
And then the
Hamiltonian just equal

00:59:37.690 --> 00:59:45.290 align:middle line:84%
to i psi bar gamma i
partial i minus m psi.

00:59:45.290 --> 00:59:50.290 align:middle line:90%


00:59:50.290 --> 00:59:52.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
Hamiltonian density.

00:59:52.000 --> 01:00:01.350 align:middle line:90%


01:00:01.350 --> 01:00:04.770 align:middle line:84%
So we now then have--
now, this just goes back

01:00:04.770 --> 01:00:06.000 align:middle line:90%
to the standard formalism.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:08.660 align:middle line:90%


01:00:08.660 --> 01:00:10.340 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

01:00:10.340 --> 01:00:11.000 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:13.248 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So can we still
interpret psi dagger

01:00:13.248 --> 01:00:16.570 align:middle line:90%
as a different field than psi?

01:00:16.570 --> 01:00:19.216 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: it's
canonical momentum.

01:00:19.216 --> 01:00:21.482 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So it's no longer
two different fields?

01:00:21.482 --> 01:00:23.690 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it's no
longer two different fields.

01:00:23.690 --> 01:00:26.230 align:middle line:84%
For example, if there are
two different fields, then

01:00:26.230 --> 01:00:29.110 align:middle line:84%
psi and psi dagger,
they should commute.

01:00:29.110 --> 01:00:31.300 align:middle line:84%
But now, since they
become canonical momentum,

01:00:31.300 --> 01:00:34.010 align:middle line:90%
they no longer commute.

01:00:34.010 --> 01:00:35.020 align:middle line:90%
yes?

01:00:35.020 --> 01:00:37.930 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: If you take psi bar
and then you bring the, you pull

01:00:37.930 --> 01:00:42.760 align:middle line:84%
out the gamma 0, isn't this
just like the right-hand side

01:00:42.760 --> 01:00:46.090 align:middle line:84%
of the-- like our earlier
version of the Dirac equation--

01:00:46.090 --> 01:00:50.944 align:middle line:84%
the one where you
like [INAUDIBLE]??

01:00:50.944 --> 01:00:52.563 align:middle line:84%
Like, the one with
the alpha and beta,

01:00:52.563 --> 01:00:54.730 align:middle line:84%
like the other Dirac equation
we wrote down earlier?

01:00:54.730 --> 01:00:56.650 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's right.

01:00:56.650 --> 01:00:59.800 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it's very-- essentially
just that Hamiltonian.

01:00:59.800 --> 01:01:01.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

01:01:01.090 --> 01:01:02.710 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:01:02.710 --> 01:01:05.300 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Is there not
a problem with this

01:01:05.300 --> 01:01:07.725 align:middle line:90%
treating the time differently?

01:01:07.725 --> 01:01:10.620 align:middle line:84%
Is it no longer
Lorentz invariant?

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:12.060 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so when you--

01:01:12.060 --> 01:01:17.790 align:middle line:84%
yeah, when we do the client
encoding equation in the scalar

01:01:17.790 --> 01:01:20.250 align:middle line:84%
theory, when you
quantize, you always

01:01:20.250 --> 01:01:22.230 align:middle line:90%
have to treat time differently.

01:01:22.230 --> 01:01:28.590 align:middle line:84%
And then the Lorentz
symmetry come out

01:01:28.590 --> 01:01:31.830 align:middle line:90%
in the property of the state.

01:01:31.830 --> 01:01:34.020 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, but you always--

01:01:34.020 --> 01:01:39.520 align:middle line:84%
when you quantize, you always
have to treat time separately.

01:01:39.520 --> 01:01:40.210 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:01:40.210 --> 01:01:40.791 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So now we have
the momentum operator,

01:01:40.791 --> 01:01:42.374 align:middle line:84%
its just the complex
conjugate of phi?

01:01:42.374 --> 01:01:47.070 align:middle line:90%


01:01:47.070 --> 01:01:48.434 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, exactly.

01:01:48.434 --> 01:01:52.174 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: So this like, its
still like constrained.

01:01:52.174 --> 01:01:54.665 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, it's a--

01:01:54.665 --> 01:02:03.240 align:middle line:90%


01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:04.650 align:middle line:90%
yeah, this is just--

01:02:04.650 --> 01:02:06.970 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so that's why we call
this a constrained system.

01:02:06.970 --> 01:02:09.430 align:middle line:84%
But now, I'm just
giving you a shortcut

01:02:09.430 --> 01:02:13.620 align:middle line:84%
so that we have to don't
have to go through this--

01:02:13.620 --> 01:02:18.638 align:middle line:84%
yeah, the intricacy of
constrained quantization.

01:02:18.638 --> 01:02:21.740 align:middle line:90%


01:02:21.740 --> 01:02:24.980 align:middle line:84%
So now, the canonical
quantization becomes easy.

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:28.920 align:middle line:90%
So now, this is my momentum.

01:02:28.920 --> 01:02:33.670 align:middle line:84%
So now, we just have the
canonical quantization.

01:02:33.670 --> 01:02:42.640 align:middle line:90%


01:02:42.640 --> 01:02:46.360 align:middle line:84%
I think today, we may
have unfortunate timing.

01:02:46.360 --> 01:02:47.980 align:middle line:90%
So now, become psi--

01:02:47.980 --> 01:02:49.300 align:middle line:90%
is coordinate.

01:02:49.300 --> 01:02:52.540 align:middle line:90%


01:02:52.540 --> 01:02:54.700 align:middle line:90%
And now, we have psi dagger.

01:02:54.700 --> 01:03:00.670 align:middle line:84%
We have pi psi, which
is the momentum.

01:03:00.670 --> 01:03:09.340 align:middle line:84%
So this, by definition, should
give you the delta function, so

01:03:09.340 --> 01:03:11.180 align:middle line:90%
equal time correlation function.

01:03:11.180 --> 01:03:12.820 align:middle line:90%
So here, we should--

01:03:12.820 --> 01:03:15.380 align:middle line:84%
because remember,
this is a four vector,

01:03:15.380 --> 01:03:17.660 align:middle line:84%
so this also have
four components.

01:03:17.660 --> 01:03:22.930 align:middle line:84%
So let me just now
suppress this subscript psi

01:03:22.930 --> 01:03:26.440 align:middle line:84%
because there's only
one variable here now.

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:28.430 align:middle line:84%
So here, there's
also coefficient--

01:03:28.430 --> 01:03:30.850 align:middle line:84%
so this is also
four vector beta,

01:03:30.850 --> 01:03:33.520 align:middle line:84%
and then here should
be delta alpha beta.

01:03:33.520 --> 01:03:35.290 align:middle line:84%
So alpha beta are
spinor indices.

01:03:35.290 --> 01:03:43.060 align:middle line:90%


01:03:43.060 --> 01:03:44.340 align:middle line:90%
So if you impose--

01:03:44.340 --> 01:03:51.190 align:middle line:84%
and this is equivalent
just to psi alpha t,

01:03:51.190 --> 01:04:06.830 align:middle line:84%
x psi dagger beta t, x prime
equal to i delta alpha beta

01:04:06.830 --> 01:04:08.020 align:middle line:90%
x x minus prime.

01:04:08.020 --> 01:04:15.480 align:middle line:90%


01:04:15.480 --> 01:04:22.560 align:middle line:84%
And so we can now
expand psi x in terms

01:04:22.560 --> 01:04:24.910 align:middle line:90%
of complete set of solutions.

01:04:24.910 --> 01:04:29.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
step of the quantization.

01:04:29.380 --> 01:04:32.940 align:middle line:84%
So first is-- this is
the commutation relation.

01:04:32.940 --> 01:04:34.950 align:middle line:84%
So the second
step-- remember, we

01:04:34.950 --> 01:04:39.270 align:middle line:84%
can expand the psi in
terms of complete basis

01:04:39.270 --> 01:04:41.460 align:middle line:90%
of classical solutions.

01:04:41.460 --> 01:04:45.540 align:middle line:90%
So psi x just equal to--

01:04:45.540 --> 01:04:48.465 align:middle line:84%
again, we integrate over
all spatial momentum.

01:04:48.465 --> 01:04:51.430 align:middle line:90%


01:04:51.430 --> 01:04:55.870 align:middle line:84%
Again, we use this
factor for convenience

01:04:55.870 --> 01:04:57.820 align:middle line:90%
as in the scalar case.

01:04:57.820 --> 01:05:01.800 align:middle line:84%
And now, we just need to sum
over all possible solutions.

01:05:01.800 --> 01:05:09.960 align:middle line:84%
So here, we have a sum
over s equal to 1 and 2.

01:05:09.960 --> 01:05:21.170 align:middle line:84%
So we have-- then we have
ak s us exponential ik x.

01:05:21.170 --> 01:05:25.115 align:middle line:90%
And then plus bk--

01:05:25.115 --> 01:05:25.615 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

01:05:25.615 --> 01:05:28.140 align:middle line:90%


01:05:28.140 --> 01:05:29.850 align:middle line:90%
k should be here-- sorry.

01:05:29.850 --> 01:05:38.840 align:middle line:84%
bk s and vs
exponential minus ik x.

01:05:38.840 --> 01:05:43.940 align:middle line:90%


01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:46.890 align:middle line:90%
So these are the complete--

01:05:46.890 --> 01:05:50.040 align:middle line:84%
because complete set of
solution are u and v.

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:52.935 align:middle line:84%
And we call the
coefficients of a and b,

01:05:52.935 --> 01:05:56.430 align:middle line:84%
so let me call it b dagger as we
did for the complex scalar case

01:05:56.430 --> 01:05:59.040 align:middle line:90%
before.

01:05:59.040 --> 01:06:02.430 align:middle line:84%
So we-- so the coefficient,
we call them a and b.

01:06:02.430 --> 01:06:05.250 align:middle line:90%
Actually, it doesn't matter.

01:06:05.250 --> 01:06:06.930 align:middle line:90%
We call it b.

01:06:06.930 --> 01:06:08.880 align:middle line:90%
Actually, let me just call it b.

01:06:08.880 --> 01:06:12.180 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so you can just--
you have u and v,

01:06:12.180 --> 01:06:14.630 align:middle line:84%
and then the coefficient
will be a and b.

01:06:14.630 --> 01:06:19.575 align:middle line:90%


01:06:19.575 --> 01:06:30.650 align:middle line:84%
And so now, you
can just plug this.

01:06:30.650 --> 01:06:36.160 align:middle line:84%
So if this equation is 1
and this equation is 2,

01:06:36.160 --> 01:06:38.770 align:middle line:84%
and you take the complex
conjugate, psi dagger,

01:06:38.770 --> 01:06:41.350 align:middle line:84%
you can plug it in here to
find what's the commutation

01:06:41.350 --> 01:06:42.748 align:middle line:90%
relation between a and b.

01:06:42.748 --> 01:06:46.960 align:middle line:90%


01:06:46.960 --> 01:06:51.895 align:middle line:90%
So you find that the--

01:06:51.895 --> 01:06:54.980 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.980 --> 01:07:03.030 align:middle line:90%
yeah, so plug 2 into 1.

01:07:03.030 --> 01:07:19.750 align:middle line:84%
So you find the commutation
relation ak s ak prime p, then

01:07:19.750 --> 01:07:29.630 align:middle line:90%
equal to bk s and bk prime t.

01:07:29.630 --> 01:07:39.350 align:middle line:84%
Then, equal to 2 pi cubed delta
st, delta 3 k minus k prime.

01:07:39.350 --> 01:07:45.250 align:middle line:90%


01:07:45.250 --> 01:07:49.990 align:middle line:84%
So now-- and you can
also define the vacuum.

01:07:49.990 --> 01:08:15.770 align:middle line:90%


01:08:15.770 --> 01:08:19.340 align:middle line:84%
And all other
commutators are 0--

01:08:19.340 --> 01:08:20.494 align:middle line:90%
with all others 0.

01:08:20.494 --> 01:08:26.840 align:middle line:90%


01:08:26.840 --> 01:08:31.310 align:middle line:84%
And you can also
define the vacuum,

01:08:31.310 --> 01:08:40.569 align:middle line:84%
as we did for the scalar case,
to be annihilated by ak and bk.

01:08:40.569 --> 01:08:51.620 align:middle line:90%


01:08:51.620 --> 01:08:56.240 align:middle line:84%
And now, you can, in principle,
build your Hilbert space.

01:08:56.240 --> 01:08:56.960 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:08:56.960 --> 01:08:58.943 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: For equation
one up there,

01:08:58.943 --> 01:09:04.620 align:middle line:84%
are you supposed to not have
factor pi just because momentum

01:09:04.620 --> 01:09:07.080 align:middle line:90%
is i psi dagger?

01:09:07.080 --> 01:09:07.878 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:09:07.878 --> 01:09:08.670 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: And then--

01:09:08.670 --> 01:09:09.545 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Oh, right.

01:09:09.545 --> 01:09:12.220 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, there's no--
yeah, thank you.

01:09:12.220 --> 01:09:13.109 align:middle line:90%
There's no i here.

01:09:13.109 --> 01:09:15.399 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because the
momentum is i psi dagger.

01:09:15.399 --> 01:09:22.859 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, there's no i anymore--
just the delta alpha beta.

01:09:22.859 --> 01:09:28.130 align:middle line:84%
So all look pretty
straightforward,

01:09:28.130 --> 01:09:31.269 align:middle line:90%
but you actually have problems.

01:09:31.269 --> 01:09:34.660 align:middle line:90%


01:09:34.660 --> 01:09:37.160 align:middle line:90%
You actually have problems.

01:09:37.160 --> 01:09:49.170 align:middle line:84%
So the first problem some
of you may be already asking

01:09:49.170 --> 01:09:55.300 align:middle line:84%
in your head, is
that, are we supposed

01:09:55.300 --> 01:09:58.820 align:middle line:90%
to describe spin-half particles?

01:09:58.820 --> 01:10:03.400 align:middle line:84%
But if we are suppose to
describe spin-half particles,

01:10:03.400 --> 01:10:05.200 align:middle line:90%
then why do we find the bosons?

01:10:05.200 --> 01:10:09.030 align:middle line:84%
So these are commutation
relations for bosons.

01:10:09.030 --> 01:10:11.760 align:middle line:90%
It's because they commute.

01:10:11.760 --> 01:10:16.960 align:middle line:84%
So different k-- sorry, I
think I'm missing dagger.

01:10:16.960 --> 01:10:17.460 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:10:17.460 --> 01:10:20.550 align:middle line:90%


01:10:20.550 --> 01:10:25.310 align:middle line:84%
So different ak, they
commute with each other.

01:10:25.310 --> 01:10:27.140 align:middle line:84%
As we discussed in
the scalar case,

01:10:27.140 --> 01:10:32.660 align:middle line:84%
when the a mu all commute with
each other, this is boson.

01:10:32.660 --> 01:10:34.190 align:middle line:84%
It means the
particle you created,

01:10:34.190 --> 01:10:38.750 align:middle line:84%
you can exchange
them and don't--

01:10:38.750 --> 01:10:41.000 align:middle line:84%
yeah, you can arbitrarily
exchange them.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:42.800 align:middle line:90%
It's symmetric.

01:10:42.800 --> 01:10:48.542 align:middle line:84%
But fermions, they are
supposed to be Pauli principle.

01:10:48.542 --> 01:10:50.000 align:middle line:84%
So you're supposed
to get the minus

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:52.160 align:middle line:90%
sign when you exchange them.

01:10:52.160 --> 01:10:55.870 align:middle line:84%
So this cannot-- this
doesn't look to be right.

01:10:55.870 --> 01:10:59.260 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- the
first thing it seems

01:10:59.260 --> 01:11:05.720 align:middle line:84%
to be we were finding
bosons rather than fermions.

01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And the second is that now if
you find that the Hamiltonian--

01:11:08.750 --> 01:11:12.430 align:middle line:90%


01:11:12.430 --> 01:11:14.620 align:middle line:84%
so now, if you try to
find the Hamiltonian--

01:11:14.620 --> 01:11:18.360 align:middle line:90%


01:11:18.360 --> 01:11:25.020 align:middle line:84%
so H is just the integration
of this Hamiltonian density.

01:11:25.020 --> 01:11:32.390 align:middle line:90%


01:11:32.390 --> 01:11:34.580 align:middle line:90%
And you can just plug it in--

01:11:34.580 --> 01:11:38.210 align:middle line:84%
plug that expression for
Hamiltonian density in.

01:11:38.210 --> 01:11:40.370 align:middle line:90%
Where is my Hamiltonian density?

01:11:40.370 --> 01:11:46.930 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, plug that in, and
then you will find the--

01:11:46.930 --> 01:11:49.970 align:middle line:90%


01:11:49.970 --> 01:11:56.300 align:middle line:84%
yeah so you find just
this just given by i d3

01:11:56.300 --> 01:12:02.420 align:middle line:84%
x psi bar gamma i
partial i minus m psi.

01:12:02.420 --> 01:12:11.790 align:middle line:90%


01:12:11.790 --> 01:12:15.990 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you plug them in, you
just plug them in-- plug this

01:12:15.990 --> 01:12:17.430 align:middle line:90%
mode expansion in--

01:12:17.430 --> 01:12:19.410 align:middle line:90%
and then you find actually--

01:12:19.410 --> 01:12:22.990 align:middle line:90%


01:12:22.990 --> 01:12:24.880 align:middle line:84%
then you find the
following expression--

01:12:24.880 --> 01:12:34.580 align:middle line:90%


01:12:34.580 --> 01:12:37.190 align:middle line:90%
omega k.

01:12:37.190 --> 01:12:41.940 align:middle line:90%
And you sum over s from 1 to 2.

01:12:41.940 --> 01:12:47.220 align:middle line:84%
And then you find
it's given by ak

01:12:47.220 --> 01:13:05.160 align:middle line:84%
s dagger ak s minus
bk s dagger bk

01:13:05.160 --> 01:13:11.290 align:middle line:84%
s, and then up to some
infinite constants.

01:13:11.290 --> 01:13:15.450 align:middle line:84%
So now, you see something
problematic here.

01:13:15.450 --> 01:13:17.250 align:middle line:90%
So what's problematic you see?

01:13:17.250 --> 01:13:22.000 align:middle line:90%


01:13:22.000 --> 01:13:22.500 align:middle line:90%
Yes?

01:13:22.500 --> 01:13:24.780 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: The energy can
be arbitrarily small.

01:13:24.780 --> 01:13:27.840 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, energy
is not positive definite

01:13:27.840 --> 01:13:29.070 align:middle line:90%
because of this minus sign.

01:13:29.070 --> 01:13:35.600 align:middle line:90%


01:13:35.600 --> 01:13:40.550 align:middle line:84%
So this minus sign tells
you that if you excite

01:13:40.550 --> 01:13:45.140 align:middle line:84%
a lot of these b particles,
you can make the energy

01:13:45.140 --> 01:13:48.200 align:middle line:84%
as negative as you want,
and then the theory

01:13:48.200 --> 01:13:49.850 align:middle line:90%
don't make sense.

01:13:49.850 --> 01:13:54.510 align:middle line:84%
And then this is a theory with
energy unbounded from below.

01:13:54.510 --> 01:13:57.990 align:middle line:84%
It's a theory with energy
unbounded from below.

01:13:57.990 --> 01:14:02.105 align:middle line:84%
So that means this
vacuum is unstable.

01:14:02.105 --> 01:14:16.970 align:middle line:90%


01:14:16.970 --> 01:14:19.760 align:middle line:84%
So there must be something
wrong with this procedure.

01:14:19.760 --> 01:14:24.080 align:middle line:90%


01:14:24.080 --> 01:14:28.170 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out that there's a
very quick fix to this problem,

01:14:28.170 --> 01:14:34.160 align:middle line:84%
and this quick fix was
invented by Jordan.

01:14:34.160 --> 01:14:38.660 align:middle line:84%
So he recognized
that if you don't

01:14:38.660 --> 01:14:41.240 align:middle line:84%
do the standard
commutation relation--

01:14:41.240 --> 01:14:43.910 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.910 --> 01:14:48.910 align:middle line:84%
if you do instead
of commutator--

01:14:48.910 --> 01:14:52.060 align:middle line:84%
here, you change it
to anti-commutator.

01:14:52.060 --> 01:14:59.800 align:middle line:90%


01:14:59.800 --> 01:15:02.350 align:middle line:84%
Remember, this bracket--
this curly bracket

01:15:02.350 --> 01:15:04.270 align:middle line:90%
means anticommutator.

01:15:04.270 --> 01:15:05.980 align:middle line:84%
And that means that
here, you change it

01:15:05.980 --> 01:15:15.790 align:middle line:84%
to anticommutator, and then
still with the same thing--

01:15:15.790 --> 01:15:30.490 align:middle line:90%


01:15:30.490 --> 01:15:35.040 align:middle line:84%
and now this becomes
anti-commutator.

01:15:35.040 --> 01:15:48.050 align:middle line:90%


01:15:48.050 --> 01:15:49.100 align:middle line:90%
So let me see.

01:15:49.100 --> 01:15:54.380 align:middle line:90%


01:15:54.380 --> 01:15:56.520 align:middle line:84%
I just want to make
sure I get the--

01:15:56.520 --> 01:15:58.925 align:middle line:90%


01:15:58.925 --> 01:16:00.550 align:middle line:84%
yeah, if we change
anti-commutator also

01:16:00.550 --> 01:16:04.540 align:middle line:84%
from the convention, you
change this to dagger.

01:16:04.540 --> 01:16:07.390 align:middle line:84%
Now you change this to dagger
as we did for the complex scalar

01:16:07.390 --> 01:16:08.080 align:middle line:90%
case.

01:16:08.080 --> 01:16:10.400 align:middle line:90%
And then you just get this.

01:16:10.400 --> 01:16:13.180 align:middle line:84%
And now, if you do that, and
then this becomes plus sign.

01:16:13.180 --> 01:16:18.980 align:middle line:90%


01:16:18.980 --> 01:16:22.550 align:middle line:84%
And now, not only this
becomes plus sign--

01:16:22.550 --> 01:16:30.740 align:middle line:84%
and also all different ak
for different s and t--

01:16:30.740 --> 01:16:32.630 align:middle line:84%
they anti-commute
with each other.

01:16:32.630 --> 01:16:42.840 align:middle line:90%


01:16:42.840 --> 01:16:45.590 align:middle line:90%
They anticommute each other.

01:16:45.590 --> 01:16:51.070 align:middle line:84%
So anticommute each other means
that if you create a particle--

01:16:51.070 --> 01:16:53.720 align:middle line:90%
for example, ak dagger--

01:16:53.720 --> 01:16:58.400 align:middle line:84%
and you create another
particle, ak prime dagger on 0,

01:16:58.400 --> 01:17:00.635 align:middle line:90%
and now these two anticommute.

01:17:00.635 --> 01:17:04.300 align:middle line:84%
It means when you exchange
all, you get the minus sign.

01:17:04.300 --> 01:17:06.820 align:middle line:84%
That precisely gives
you the minus sign

01:17:06.820 --> 01:17:08.530 align:middle line:90%
in the Pauli principle--

01:17:08.530 --> 01:17:14.230 align:middle line:90%
in the statistics for fermions.

01:17:14.230 --> 01:17:19.360 align:middle line:84%
And so changing this thing
to the anti-commutator--

01:17:19.360 --> 01:17:22.660 align:middle line:90%
and so solves all your problem.

01:17:22.660 --> 01:17:25.420 align:middle line:84%
And your energy now
is bounded from below,

01:17:25.420 --> 01:17:28.150 align:middle line:84%
and then you actually
now actually describe

01:17:28.150 --> 01:17:32.290 align:middle line:84%
some particles which
obey the Pauli principle.

01:17:32.290 --> 01:17:38.500 align:middle line:90%


01:17:38.500 --> 01:17:48.130 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, I think we still
have 1 minute left, but we--

01:17:48.130 --> 01:17:52.540 align:middle line:84%
but it's a good time to stop,
because otherwise, other things

01:17:52.540 --> 01:17:53.900 align:middle line:90%
will take more time.

01:17:53.900 --> 01:17:57.220 align:middle line:84%
So let me just make
a couple remark

01:17:57.220 --> 01:18:02.470 align:middle line:84%
why the commutator-- why
here, you need to do something

01:18:02.470 --> 01:18:03.580 align:middle line:90%
unconventional.

01:18:03.580 --> 01:18:10.990 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.990 --> 01:18:12.910 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at this
Hamiltonian density--

01:18:12.910 --> 01:18:19.290 align:middle line:90%


01:18:19.290 --> 01:18:25.240 align:middle line:84%
so even without doing
this calculation,

01:18:25.240 --> 01:18:30.790 align:middle line:84%
you can already conclude from
here that this H cannot be

01:18:30.790 --> 01:18:32.920 align:middle line:84%
bounded from below for
the following reason.

01:18:32.920 --> 01:18:36.320 align:middle line:90%


01:18:36.320 --> 01:18:38.890 align:middle line:90%
So from the Dirac equation--

01:18:38.890 --> 01:18:40.120 align:middle line:90%
let me just erase here.

01:18:40.120 --> 01:18:43.390 align:middle line:90%


01:18:43.390 --> 01:18:47.230 align:middle line:84%
So from the Dirac
equation, you have

01:18:47.230 --> 01:18:53.620 align:middle line:84%
gamma mu partial mu
minus m psi equal to 0.

01:18:53.620 --> 01:18:59.230 align:middle line:84%
So that means that the gamma
i partial i minus m psi

01:18:59.230 --> 01:19:02.710 align:middle line:84%
is equal to minus
gamma 0 partial 0 psi.

01:19:02.710 --> 01:19:05.380 align:middle line:90%


01:19:05.380 --> 01:19:13.360 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you plug
this equation into here,

01:19:13.360 --> 01:19:15.980 align:middle line:90%
and then what you get--

